'''Don Dodge''' (born 1957)<ref name=cuts>"Microsoft 's job cuts deeper than forecast". ''The Seattle Times''. November 5, 2009.</ref> is a Developer Advocate for [[Google]], which requires that he helps developers build applications on the company's platforms. Prior to working at Google, Dodge was a start-up [[Technology evangelist|evangelist]] at [[Microsoft]], where he was one of their most visible employees following [[Robert Scoble]]'s departure in 2006.<ref name=boston>[http://www.boston.com/business/technology/innoeco/2010/02/how_to_get_laid_off_the_don_do.html "How to get laid off: the Don Dodge approach"]. ''Boston Globe''. Retrieved July 8, 2010.</ref>
==Biography== Dodge received a [[bachelor of science]] from the [[University of Southern Maine]], majoring in [[accounting]]. Afterward, he received an [[MBA]] from New Hampshire College (now [[Southern New Hampshire University]]). Following graduation, Dodge worked at a number of technology companies, including [[Digital Equipment]], [[Forte Software]], [[AltaVista]], [[Napster]], and [[Bowstreet]]. Afterward, he worked at [[Groove Networks]]. When the company was acquired by Microsoft, Dodge became Director of Business Development for Microsoft's Emerging Business Team. He was also known as a "start-up [[Technology evangelist|evangelist]]" for Microsoft.<ref>[http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2009/december/29/chinwong.isx&d=/2009/december/29 "Would you fire Steve Ballmer?"]. ''Manila Standard Today''. Retrieved July 8, 2010.</ref> Focusing on the [[New England]] area and based in [[New Hampshire]],<ref name=boston /> Dodge often worked specifically with companies in the greater [[Boston]] area, to help them use Microsoft products for their companies.<ref name=tcn /> Dodge felt positively towards [[Ray Ozzie]], CEO of Groove Networks, whom replaced [[Bill Gates]] as [[Chief Software Architect]] at Microsoft following Gates' retirement announcement.<ref>"In giant footsteps". ''Financial Times''. June 19, 2006.</ref>
Dodge was laid off from Microsoft on November 5, 2009,<ref name=cuts /> and then he became a Developer Advocate for Google,<ref>"Startup guru Don Dodge among Microsoft layoffs". ''Seattle Post-Intelligencer''. November 4, 2009.</ref> where he helps developers build applications on Google's platforms, as well as help [[venture capitalist]]s and [[start-up companies]] work with Google.<ref name=tcn /> After moving to Google, Dodge switched from using a [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]-based computer to a [[Mac OS X|Mac]]-based one, a move which he enjoys greatly.<ref>"Mac vs. PC – ex Microsoft evangelist on his switch". ''Seattle Post-Intelligencer''. February 2, 2010.</ref> In 2010, Dodge compared Google to Microsoft when it was a ten-year-old company, indicating that it still had a lot of growth ahead of it.<ref name=spi>"Ex-Softie: Google is like Microsoft at 10 years old". ''Seattle Post-Intelligencer''. June 18, 2010.</ref> Dodge writes a personal blog called "The Next Big Thing".<ref name=tcn>[http://www.thecapitalnetwork.org/about.advisors.DDodge.php "Don Dodge"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517151832/http://www.thecapitalnetwork.org/about.advisors.DDodge.php |date=May 17, 2010 }}. The Capital Network. Retrieved July 8, 2010.</ref>
